    "stem": "A chemist measures $K_1 = 1.2 \\times 10^{-3}$ at $T_1 = 300\\,\\text{K}$ for the gas-phase reaction\n$$\\text{A}(g) \\rightleftharpoons \\text{B}(g)$$\nand finds $K_2 = 4.8 \\times 10^{-3}$ at $T_2 = 350\\,\\text{K}$. Which conclusion is best supported by applying the Van't Hoff equation to these data?\n\n$$\\ln\\frac{K_2}{K_1} = -\\frac{\\Delta H^\\circ}{R}\\left(\\frac{1}{T_2} - \\frac{1}{T_1}\\right)$$",
    "answer_key": "A) $\\Delta H^\\circ > 0$; raising temperature shifts equilibrium toward products because the reaction is endothermic.\n\n**Reasoning:** $K_2 > K_1$ when $T_2 > T_1$, so $K$ increases with temperature. From the Van't Hoff equation:\n$$\\ln\\frac{K_2}{K_1} = \\ln\\frac{4.8 \\times 10^{-3}}{1.2 \\times 10^{-3}} = \\ln 4 \\approx +1.386$$\nThe factor $-\\left(\\frac{1}{T_2} - \\frac{1}{T_1}\\right) = -\\left(\\frac{1}{350} - \\frac{1}{T_1}\\right) = -(-4.76 \\times 10^{-4}) > 0$. For the product of $\\frac{-\\Delta H^\\circ}{R} $ and a positive number to be positive, $\\Delta H^\\circ$ must be positive. A positive $\\Delta H^key_val$, $\\Delta H^\\circ$ must be positive. A positive $\\Delta H^\\circ$ is endothermic; per Le Chatelier's principle (and confirmed by the Van't Hoff table), raising $T$ increases $K$, shifting equilibrium toward products.",
